To print the given string containing a hexadecimal escape sequence in Python, you can follow this code snippet:

```python
print("\\x9d")
```

This will output `'\x9d'` (a backslash followed by the escaped hexadecimal value). Note that if you want to actually represent the character corresponding to the hexadecimal value '\x9d', you should convert it into its actual character form. Here's how you might do that:

```python
print(chr(int('9d', 16)))
```

This will output the actual character '¬'. Remember that interpreting escape sequences depends on the programming environment; in some environments, you might see a visible symbol instead of just the escape sequence itself.
